HEADWORD: Brocade
<hw>Bro*cade"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.
<ets>brocado</ets> (cf. It. <ets>broccato</ets>, F. <ets>brocart</ets>),
fr. LL. <ets>brocare</ets> *prick, to figure (textile fabrics), to
emboss (linen), to stitch. See <er>Broach</er>.]</ety> <def>Silk stuff,
woven with gold and silver threads, or ornamented with raised flowers,
foliage, etc.; -- also applied to other stuffs thus wrought and
enriched.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A gala suit of faded <qex>brocade</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brocaded</ent>⟦br⟧
